  "prompt": "How early should I start ACT prep?",
  "response": "Starting ACT prep early can significantly improve your chances of achieving your target score. Here\u2019s a general timeline to consider:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Baseline Assessment: 6-12 Months Before the Test**  \n- Take a **full-length practice ACT test** to assess your current skill level and identify strengths and weaknesses.  \n- Research your target score based on the colleges you\u2019re interested in.  \n\n---\n\n### **2. Start Consistent Prep: 3-6 Months Before the Test**  \n- Begin a **structured study plan** (e.g., 2-4 hours per week) focusing on weak areas.  \n- Use official ACT prep materials, practice tests, and review content (math, English, reading, science).  \n- Familiarize yourself with the test format, timing, and question types.  \n\n---\n\n### **3. Intensive Prep: 1-3 Months Before the Test**  \n- Increase study time to 5-10 hours per week.  \n- Take **timed practice tests** regularly to build endurance and improve time management.  \n- Review mistakes thoroughly and focus on mastering difficult concepts.  \n\n---\n\n### **4. Final Review: 2 Weeks Before the Test**  \n- Take 1-2 more full-length practice tests under real test conditions.  \n- Focus on **test-taking strategies** (e.g., pacing, guessing, and eliminating wrong answers).  \n- Review high-yield topics and formulas (especially for math and science).  \n\n---\n\n### **Key Tips:**  \n- **Standard Prep Time:** For most students, **3-6 months of consistent prep** is ideal.  \n- **Customize Your Plan:** If you have a busy schedule or need a large score improvement, start earlier (6+ months).  \n- **Practice Tests:** Take at least 4-6 full-length practice tests before the actual test.  \n\nBy starting early, you\u2019ll have time to improve gradually, reduce stress, and maximize your score potential. Good luck!",
